<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-06-08</title>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> OpenSkill is the clearest seed for a durable research thread. It formalizes how agents can self-improve after deployment without target-task supervision — a design pattern that outlasts any single model generation.</p>
</callout>

<p>This run covers <b>2026-06-07 to 2026-06-08</b>. The pool was small — 20 new papers — but three strong threads emerged: world models as controllable embodied interfaces, real-time 3D perception for streaming video, and agents that build their own learning loops from open-world resources. All three deep-dived papers are conceptually ambitious and empirically solid, though none has released code yet.</p>

<h1>World Simulation for Embodied Agents</h1>

<p>Two papers this week tackle the same frontier — how world models can serve embodied agents — from opposite directions. AnchorWorld <i>generates</i> egocentric experience conditioned on full-body motion and user-specified scene anchors. Astra (Thinking with Imagination) <i>reasons</i> about spatial relationships by querying a world simulator for missing viewpoints. Together they show the field moving past passive video generation toward interactive, agent-facing world models.</p>

