<h2>AnchorWorld: Embodied Egocentric World Simulation with View-based Evolution Customization</h2>
<p>Yu Li et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.07326">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.07326">PDF</a></p>

<p>AnchorWorld generates 77-frame egocentric videos from two control signals: full-body human motion (SMPL-X parameters) and a set of <b>anchor views</b> — each an RGB image with a 6-DoF pose and a text evolution prompt. The motion drives the camera and body; the anchors pin local scene appearance to 3D locations and dictate how those regions change over time.</p>

<p>The architectural insight is a <b>hybrid-view training</b> strategy. Egocentric videos provide sparse motion supervision because most body parts are out of frame. AnchorWorld pairs first-person videos with third-person footage of the same motion, treating the camera as a projection parameter. The model pre-trains on 301K third-person videos (200K internal + 101K synthetic UE), then adapts to egocentric data with the same motion sequences rendered from the head viewpoint. A spatial pose attention mechanism concatenates video tokens with motion and camera tokens along the spatial dimension, updates them via self-attention, and truncates the pose tokens:</p>

<p><latex>\mathbf{T} = [\mathbf{z}_v^{(t)}; \mathbf{z}_m; \mathbf{z}_c] \in \mathbb{R}^{f' \times (hw + k + 1) \times d}</latex></p>
<p><latex>\mathbf{z}_v^{(t)} = \mathbf{z}_v^{(t)} + \text{Truncate}\left(\text{Attn}(W_Q \mathbf{T}, W_K \mathbf{T}, W_V \mathbf{T})\right)</latex></p>

<p>For world customization, anchor images are in-context concatenated with video latents. 3D RoPE distinguishes multiple anchors by frame-axis position. Text evolution prompts are injected via <b>masked cross-attention</b> — each prompt's keys are visible only to its corresponding anchor tokens and the generated video tokens, preventing cross-anchor interference.</p>

<p>The quantitative results are strong: AnchorWorld beats reimplemented PlayerOne and CaM baselines on scene consistency, camera accuracy, and text alignment. The most impressive qualitative result is <b>out-of-sight evolution</b> — the model correctly infers that a person stands up from a sofa even when that action is initially outside the egocentric field of view, because the anchor view specified the region and the evolution prompt described the action.</p>

<p>But the ablations tell a more nuanced story. The largest gains come from Stage I third-person pretraining and projection-based control, not from the anchor-view mechanism itself. Removing anchor-view pose or RoPE degrades metrics by only 1–2%. The anchor view is elegant and enables genuinely new capabilities (out-of-sight control, pose-consistent anchoring), but it is not the dominant source of improvement.</p>

<callout emoji="⚠️" background-color="light-yellow">
  <p><b>Caveats:</b> No code or data released. PlayerOne is reimplemented, not official. The 200K "internal curated dataset" is undisclosed. Hands are excluded from motion estimation. Limited to 77 frames with no long-horizon evaluation.</p>
</callout>

<p><b>Verdict:</b> Track. Hybrid-view training is a genuinely useful idea for egocentric generation. The anchor-view mechanism is conceptually clean but needs stronger empirical validation and, critically, open data before it can be built upon.</p>

<hr/>

<h1>Streaming Spatial Intelligence</h1>

<p>Deploying 3D vision-language models in AR glasses or robots requires real-time operation on streaming video, not batch processing of pre-segmented clips. Stream3D-VLM is the first system to tackle this, reformulating streaming control as next-token prediction and incrementally injecting geometry priors from a feed-forward reconstruction model.</p>

