<h2>Stream3D-VLM: Online 3D Spatial Understanding with Incremental Geometry Priors</h2>
<p>Hanxun Yu et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.06891">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.06891">PDF</a></p>

<p>Stream3D-VLM is built on Qwen2.5-VL and adds three components for streaming 3D operation. First, an <b>autoregressive streaming mechanism</b> that introduces <code>&lt;SEP&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;END&gt;</code> decision tokens. The model jointly optimizes a streaming decision loss and the standard language modeling loss:</p>

<p><latex>\mathcal{L} = \lambda \mathcal{L}_{\text{stream}} + \mathcal{L}_{\text{LM}}</latex></p>

<p>where <latex>\mathcal{L}_{\text{stream}}</latex> is cross-entropy on decision tokens and <latex>\lambda = 2.0</latex> in practice. During inference, the model ingests frames at 1 FPS and decides on-the-fly whether to respond or continue watching.</p>

<p>Second, a <b>Visual-Spatial Feature Integration (VSFI)</b> module. StreamVGGT — a concurrent feed-forward 3D reconstruction model — extracts latent geometry tokens and a camera token per frame. These are fused into the 2D visual stream via cross-attention, with the 2D tokens as queries and 3D tokens as keys/values. A residual connection preserves original semantics. This design lets the model reason about object-object and object-camera spatial relationships without explicit point-cloud or mesh inputs.</p>

<p>Third, <b>Geometry-Adaptive Voxel Compression (GAVC)</b>. For long streaming sessions, visual tokens accumulate and inference latency grows. GAVC back-projects 2D patches to 3D using estimated depth, clusters them with K-Means in 3D space, and aggregates within each cluster using dual attention that weights both feature similarity and spatial proximity:</p>

<p><latex>s_j^f = \cos(\mathbf{v}_j, \bar{\mathbf{v}}_k), \quad s_j^p = \exp\left(-\|\mathbf{p}_j - \bar{\mathbf{p}}_k\|^2 / 2\sigma_k^2\right)</latex></p>
<p><latex>w_j = \alpha s_j^f + (1 - \alpha) s_j^p</latex></p>

<p>The compression preserves 3D structure while cutting tokens. At 50% retention, GAVC achieves 59.8/65.4/51.4 on numerical/multiple-choice/open-ended answers, versus 49.2/53.8/41.6 for VisionZip — a ~10-point gap that validates geometry-aware over semantics-only compression.</p>

<p>The benchmark contribution is substantial. Stream3D-Bench spans 29 tasks across five cognitive categories (ego-motion, environment measurement, object-camera relations, object chronology, object attributes) and three temporal modes (backward tracing, realtime perception, forward monitoring). The 1M+ training QA pairs are generated from ScanNet, ScanNet++, and ARKitScenes using a hybrid of rule-based templates and VLM-verified transfer.</p>

<p>The most striking result is model efficiency: the <b>4B variant reaches 55.2% on VSI-Bench</b>, beating Qwen2.5-VL-72B (37.0%) and even Gemini-2.5 Pro (51.5%). This suggests that streaming architecture and geometry priors matter more than raw parameter count for 3D spatial reasoning.</p>

<callout emoji="⚠️" background-color="light-yellow">
  <p><b>Caveats:</b> No code released. Heavy dependence on unreleased StreamVGGT model. Training data is largely templated. Real-world streaming (AR glasses, robots) is unvalidated. Indoor-only benchmarks.</p>
</callout>

<p><b>Verdict:</b> Read. Strong engineering with a clean three-part architecture and a valuable benchmark. If the authors release code, this could become a standard building block for embodied agents.</p>

<hr/>

<h1>Agents That Improve Themselves</h1>

<p>The most durable idea this week is OpenSkill's framing of open-world self-evolution. Most self-improving agents assume a usable learning loop is already present: curated skills, successful trajectories, or verifier signals. OpenSkill asks what happens when none of these exist — when the agent has only a task prompt and the open web.</p>

