<h2>OpenSkill: Open-World Self-Evolution for LLM Agents</h2>
<p>Zhiling Yan et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.06741">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.06741">PDF</a></p>

<p>OpenSkill bootstraps a learning loop from scratch in three stages. <b>Stage 1</b> retrieves task-relevant knowledge and verification anchors from the open web using a deep-research agent (Gemini). The query is carefully filtered to exclude benchmark names, preventing answer leakage. <b>Stage 2</b> drafts skills and refines them against self-built virtual tests — pytest suites generated by an independent verifier LLM that uses only the verification anchors, never ground-truth tests. A diagnostic classifier determines whether failures are bugs (self-fixable) or knowledge gaps (triggering targeted retrieval). <b>Stage 3</b> deploys the frozen skill to the target agent zero-shot.</p>

<p>The central design choice is the <b>leakage barrier</b>: ground-truth tests are invisible during skill construction and unlocked only for final evaluation. This forces the agent to build its own verification signal from independently checkable facts — reference values, statistical invariants, cross-validation procedures, documented output formats.</p>

<p>The results are the best automated pass rates on every benchmark setting tested. On SkillsBench (11 domains), OpenSkill achieves 43.6% with Opus 4.6 and 42.1% with GPT 5.2 — beating the strongest baseline by +8.9 and +8.8 points, and landing within 1–3 points of the human upper bound (44.5% / 44.8%).</p>

