<p>Perhaps more important than the absolute numbers is <b>cross-model transfer</b>. Skills built by Opus 4.6 improve Haiku, Qwen 3 Coder, DeepSeek V3, and Mistral Large by 5.5–14.8 points without any model-specific adaptation. This confirms that explicit skill artifacts are more durable than model-bound behaviors.</p>

<p>The ablations are instructive. Open-world retrieval alone contributes +6.1 points. The virtual verifier alone contributes +6.3 points. Together they yield +8.2 — the components are complementary. However, refinement peaks at 3 iterations (82.7%) and degrades at 5 (79.9%) and 10 (78.0%), suggesting overfitting to imperfect virtual feedback. The virtual verifier itself has 56.9% precision and covers 88.9% of ground-truth test intents — good enough to guide skill construction, but far from perfect.</p>

<callout emoji="⚠️" background-color="light-yellow">
  <p><b>Caveats:</b> Code not yet released. Cost is substantial (~$1,800 per full benchmark run). Heavy commercial API dependency. Manufacturing domain collapses to 0% for all methods. The virtual verifier's false-positive rate means some "passed" skills still fail ground-truth tests.</p>
</callout>

<p><b>Verdict:</b> Read. The conceptual contribution — formalizing open-world self-evolution with a leakage barrier — is more important than the specific numbers. The three-stage pipeline (acquire → verify → deploy) is a durable design pattern for agent self-improvement, though the current implementation is too API-dependent and expensive for wide adoption.</p>

<hr/>

<h1>Cross-cutting Observations</h1>

<p><b>Code release remains the critical bottleneck.</b> All three deep-dived papers are conceptually strong and empirically solid, yet none has released code. AnchorWorld's project page shows videos but no repository. Stream3D-VLM's project page has no code link. OpenSkill's GitHub is a placeholder ("Code is on the way"). This is a concerning pattern: the field is generating good ideas faster than it is making them reproducible. For a community that claims to value open science, the gap between paper publication and code release is widening, not narrowing.</p>

<p><b>World models are becoming agent-facing, not just generative.</b> AnchorWorld generates worlds. Astra reasons with generated worlds. Stream3D-VLM perceives worlds in real time. OpenSkill improves agents that operate in worlds. The common thread is that world models are no longer just video generators — they are becoming interfaces between agents and their environments. This shift from "generate pretty videos" to "enable embodied cognition" is the most important trend in this week's pool.</p>
